# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bridgeport-connecticut
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] The **1860 United States census** was the eighth census conducted in the United States, starting June 1, 1860, and lasting five months.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] It determined the population of the United States to be 31,443,321 in 33 states and 10 organized territories.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] This was an increase of 35.6 percent over the 23,191,876 persons enumerated during the 1850 census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] The total population included 3,953,760 slaves.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] By the time the 1860 census returns were ready for tabulation, the nation was sinking into the American Civil War.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] As a result, census superintendent Joseph C.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] Kennedy and his staff produced only an abbreviated set of public reports, without graphic or cartographic representations.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] The statistics did allow the census staff to produce a cartographic display, including preparing maps of Southern states, for Union field commanders.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] These maps displayed militarily vital topics, including the white population, slave population, predominant agricultural products (by county), and rail and post road transportation routes.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] Philadelphia would lose its position as the second-most-populous American city to Chicago in 1890.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] The 1860 census Schedule 1 (Free Inhabitants) was one of two schedules that counted the population of the United States; the other was Schedule 2 (Slave Inhabitants).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1860 population census, including microdata, census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series (IPUMS).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] National data reveals that farmers (owners and tenants) made up nearly 10% of utilized occupations.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] Farm laborers (wage workers) represent the next highest percent with 3.2%, followed by general laborers at 3.0%.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] More localized data shows that other occupations were common.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] In the town of Essex, Massachusetts, a large section of the women in the labor force were devoted to shoe-binding, while for men the common occupations were farming and shoe-making.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] This heavy demand of shoe-related labor reinforces the high demand for rigorous physical laborers in the economy, as supported by the data of very large amounts of farm related work as compared to most other labor options.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] IPUMS' data also notes that the share of the population that had been enrolled in school or marked as "Student" stood at 0.2%.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] This demonstrates a small rate of growth, if any, in the proficiency of the human capital of the time—the skill set a worker has to apply to the labor force, which can increase total output through increased efficiency.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1860-united-states-census] The census of 1860 was the last in which much of Southern wealth was held as slaves—still legally considered property.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The **1870 United States census** was the ninth United States census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] It was conducted by the Census Office from June 1, 1870, to August 23, 1871.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first census to provide detailed information on the African American population, only five years after the culmination of the Civil War when slaves were granted freedom.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The total population was 38,925,598 with a resident population of 38,558,371 individuals, a 22.6% increase from 1860.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census's population estimate was controversial, as many believed it underestimated the true population numbers, especially in New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 10,000.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] This was also the last federal census conducted using the US Marshal Service as enumerators.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The Census Act of 1850 established the primary machinery of the ninth census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The Census Office, working within the Department of the Interior, oversaw the recording and tabulation of results gathered by assistant marshals, who were hired and supervised by federal marshals.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Two new structural changes during the 1870 census occurred: marshals had to return the completed population questionnaire to the Census Office in September, and penalties for refusing to reply to enumerator questions were extended to encompass every question on the questionnaires.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The commonly past-used slave questionnaires were redesigned to reflect the American society after the Civil War.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The five schedules for the 1870 census were the following: General Population, Mortality, Agriculture, Products of Industry, and Social Statistics.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The general population saw a 22.6% increase to 38,555,983 individuals in 1870.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Charges of an undercount, however, were brought against Francis Amasa Walker, the Superintendent of the 1870 census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Mortality rates in 1870, in general, decreased as a fraction of the total population by <0.1% from 1860 and by 0.1% from 1850.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The lower death rates indicate that the standard of living increased, due to some exogenous factor, over the period of twenty years from 1850 to 1870.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] In terms of products of industry, total U.S. wealth increased by 17.3% from 1860 to 1870, to reach an assessed wealth of $14,178,986,732.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The four largest state contributors to this wealth were New York, Massachusetts, Pennsylvania, and Ohio, in that order.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Most of the wealth was concentrated in the developed Northeast region, as newer territories like Wyoming were beginning to develop their young economies.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] The 1870 census was the first of its kind to record the nativity of the American population.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] This social statistic helped determine which areas were more highly composed of immigrants than native-born Americans.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] New York City had the most foreign-born individuals, with 419,094 foreigners, who comprised 44.5% of the city's total population.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Louis, and San Francisco also had a great population of foreigners that made up a significant fraction of their total populations.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Therefore, a great ethnic and cultural change was witnessed from 1860 to 1870, as part of the population growth was due to immigrants moving in and a shuffling of residents across state borders.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1870 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] With especially bitter complaints coming from New York and Philadelphia claiming up to a third of the population was not counted, the President made the rare move to order a recount in those areas.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] While it was thought a large fraction of the population was not counted for being indoors in the wintry cold, newer estimates resulted in only a 2.5% increase in Philadelphia's population and a 2% increase in New York's.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] This controversy of the 1870 undercount resurfaced in 1890, when the national growth rate between 1880 and 1890 was discovered to be much lower than it was between 1870 and 1880.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Critics then asserted that the 1870 population must have been underenumerated by over 1.2 million people to account for the discrepancy between growth rates; it was presumed that the growth rate in 1880 had to be exaggerated because of the 1870 undercount.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Despite the fact that modern investigations have yet to quantify the exact effect of the undercount, most modern social scientists do not believe the undercount was as severe as 1890 investigators assumed.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/1870-united-states-census] Today most analyzers compare the 1870 undercount to the non-response rates seen in most modern census data.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Inhabited by the Paugussett Native American tribe until English colonisation in the 1600s, Bridgeport was incorporated as a town in 1821 and as a city in 1836.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum was a resident of the city and served as the town's mayor in 1871.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum built four houses in Bridgeport and housed his circus in town during winter.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the early 20th century, the city saw an economic and population boom, becoming by all measures Connecticut's chief manufacturing city by 1905.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was the site of the world's first mutual telephone exchange (1877), the first dental hygiene school (1949), and the first bank telephone bill service in the US (1981).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Inventor Harvey Hubbell II invented the first American electric plug outlet in Bridgeport in 1912.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Frisbie Pie Company was founded and operated in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The world's first Subway restaurant opened in the city's North End in 1965.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] After World War II, industrial decline and suburbanization led to the loss of major employers and affluent residents, contributing to poverty and violent crime.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Since the early 21st century, however, the city has undertaken significant redevelopment efforts, and its crime rate fell by nearly 50 percent between 2010 and 2018.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport is home to three museums; the University of Bridgeport, Housatonic Community College, and part of Sacred Heart University; and the state's only zoo.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It is officially nicknamed "Park City" due to its 35 public parks, which take up 1,300 acres.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Although none are headquartered within the city itself, more than a dozen Fortune 500 companies are based in its metropolitan area.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport has been consistently ranked by various sites as among the 25 most ethnically and culturally diverse American cities.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was inhabited by the Paugussett Native American tribe during the start of European colonization.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The earliest European communal settlement was in the historical Stratfield district, along US Route 1, known in colonial times as the King's Highway.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Close by, Mount Grove Cemetery was laid out on what was a native village that extended past the 1650s.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It is also an ancient Paugussett burial ground.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The burgeoning farming community grew and became a center of trade, shipbuilding, and whaling.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was incorporated to subsidize the Housatonic Railroad and rapidly industrialized following the rail line's connection to the New York and New Haven railroad.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was given its name because of the need for bridges over the Pequonnock River that provided a navigable port at the mouth of the river.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Manufacturing was the mainstay of the local economy until the 1970s.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The first documented European settlement within the present city limits of Bridgeport took place in 1644, centered at Black Rock Harbor and along North Avenue between Park and Briarwood Avenues.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The place was called **Pequonnock** (Quiripi for "Cleared Land"), after a band of the Paugussett, an Algonquian-speaking Native American people who occupied this area.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] One of their sacred sites was Golden Hill, which overlooked the harbor and was the location of natural springs and their planting fields.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (It has since been blasted through for construction of an expressway.) The Golden Hill Indians were granted a reservation here by the Colony of Connecticut in 1639; it lasted until 1802.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (One of the tribes acquired land for a small reservation in the late 19th century that was recognized by the state.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1659, the general court in Hartford established the official borders of the Paugussett Reservation.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport's early years were marked by residents' reliance on fishing and farming.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This was similar to the economy of the Paugussett, who had cultivated corn, beans, and squash; and fished and gathered shellfish from both the river and sound.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A village called **Newfield** began to develop around the corner of State and Water Streets in the 1760s.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The area officially became known as **Stratfield** in 1695 or 1701, due to its location between the already existing towns of *Strat*ford and Fair*field*.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] During the American Revolution, Newfield Harbor was a center of privateering.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By the time of the State of Connecticut's ratification of the Articles of Confederation in 1781, many of the local farmers held shares in vessels trading at Newfield Harbor or had begun trading in their own name.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Newfield initially expanded around the coasting trade with Boston, New York, and Baltimore and the international trade with the West Indies.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The commercial activity of the village was clustered around the wharves on the west bank of the Pequonnock, while the churches were erected inland on Broad Street.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1787, the Fairfield County Court ordered the laying out and widening of what is now State Street and Main Street in downtown Bridgeport, along the Pequannock River then Newfield.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was assumed before the Revolution that this land would grow into a city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1800, the village became the Borough of Bridgeport, the first so incorporated in the state.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was named for the Newfield or Lottery Bridge across the Pequonnock, connecting the wharves on its east and west banks.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Bank was established in 1806.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1821, the township of Bridgeport became independent of Stratford.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1821, a small community of remaining Golden Hill Pauguasett Natives, along with free blacks and runaway slaves was established in the South End along Main Street known as Little Liberia, with its own churches, schools and hotels, and served as a stop in the underground railroad.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Many remaining Paugusset Indians also lived there.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The West India trade died down around 1840, but by that time the Bridgeport Steamship Company (1824) and Bridgeport Whaling Company (1833) had been incorporated and the Housatonic Railroad chartered (1836).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The HRRC ran upstate along the Housatonic Valley, connecting with Massachusetts's Berkshire Railroad at the state line.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was chartered as Connecticut's fifth city in 1836 in order to enable the town council to secure funding (ultimately $150,000) to provide to the HRRC and ensure that it would terminate in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Naugatuck Railroad—connecting Bridgeport to Waterbury and Winsted along the Naugatuck River—was chartered in 1845 and began operation four years later.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The same year, the New York and New Haven Railroad began operation, connecting Bridgeport to New York and the other towns along the north shore of the Long Island Sound.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Now a major junction, the city began to industrialize.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The city's first immigrants were Irish Catholics who settled in the Sterling Hill section of the Hollow.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Having come to the US to escape the famine, they arrived in town during the 1830s to build the railroad.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] They mostly lived in wooden four to six family tenements, often subdivided homes.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum spent a night in Bridgeport, and there met Charles Stratton, a local dwarf.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] He soon became part of Barnum's act and a star under the name "General Tom Thumb".
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum moved to Bridgeport and built four houses in the city over the course of his life, the first being Iranistan.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1852, Barnum began an endeavor with William Noble to develop the land (inherited by Noble) on the other side of the Pequonnock River, across the river from Bridgeport to be known as "East Bridgeport" with Washington Park at the center.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The new neighborhood had homes, commerce, and factories, centered around East Main Street.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The neighborhood eventually became the East Side of Bridgeport (occasionally spelled "Eastside").
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1863, during the Civil War, the *Bridgeport Standard* ran a series of articles encouraging the creation of a public park in the city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum, William Noble and Nathaniel Wheeler to purchase the land on Long Island Sound and donating the land to the city in 1864.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The land on the shore became Seaside Park.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A second park was built near East Main Street, when in 1878, James Beardsley donated more than 100 acres (40 ha) to the city along the Pequonnock River under the condition that the land be "kept the same forever as a public park".
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Both parks were designed by Frederick Law Olmsted, known for creating Central Park.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] These two large public parks gave Bridgeport the nickname "The Park City".
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Augustine Cathedral was finished in 1869, built by the Irish who had arrived 30 year earlier.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Saint James Church, predating the Archdiocese of Hartford, was the first Catholic congregation in Fairfield County, starting with 250 members in 1842.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The congregation gave rise to St Augustine's in Sterling Hill, the seat of the Diocese of Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Following the Civil War, the town held several iron foundries and factories manufacturing firearms, metallic cartridges, horse harnesses, locks, and blinds.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Wheeler & Wilson's sewing machines were exported throughout the world.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport absorbed the West End and the village of Black Rock and its busy harbor in 1870.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum was elected mayor of the town, which afterwards served as the winter headquarters of Barnum and Bailey's Circus and Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Barnum also helped establish Fairfield County's first hospital (Conn.'s 3rd) and the Bridgeport-Port Jefferson ferry, connecting the town to Long Island.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Harvey Hubbell founded Hubbell Incorporated in Bridgeport in 1888.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Holmes & Edwards Silver Co. was founded in 1882, its wares sold nationally, and the company became part of the International Silver Company in 1898.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] (The H&E brand continued well into the 1950s and was advertised in national magazines such as *LIFE* and *Ladies' Home Journal*.) Hungarian immigrants began to arrive, which led to the Ráckόczi Hungarian Aid Association in Bridgeport in 1887 and the American Hungarian Immigrant Aid Society in 1892.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] They established themselves in the West End.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1894, Bridgeport's Slavic immigrants played a major role in the development of the Orthodox Christian faith in America when they met with Fr Alexis Toth (now Saint Alexis) and founded Holy Ghost Russian Orthodox Church in the city's Eastside.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This parish became the mother church of all Orthodox Churches in New England.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] From 1870 to 1910, Bridgeport became the largest industrial center in Connecticut; its population rose from around 25,000 to over 100,000, including thousands of Irish, Slovaks, Hungarians, Germans, English, and Italian immigrants.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Jewish migration to the city began in the 1881, with an influx of Polish, Russian, and especially Hungarian Jews calling Bridgeport home.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Jew Edwin Land grew up to invent the Polaroid.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1905, Bridgeport was already "the largest industrial center in the state, $49,381,348 was invested in manufacturing and the products being valued at $44,586,519." The city was a port of entry with its imports being valued at around $656,271 in 1908.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Singer factory joined Wheeler & Wilson in producing sewing machines and the Locomobile Company of America was a prominent early automobile manufacturer, producing a prototype of the Stanley Steamer and various luxury cars.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The town was also the center of America's corset production, responsible for 19.9% of the national total, and became the headquarters of Remington Arms following its 1912 merger with the Union Metallic Cartridge Co.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Around the time of the First World War, Bridgeport was also producing steam-fitting and heating apparatuses, brass goods, phonographs, typewriters, milling machines, brassieres, and saddles.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Brideport's Italian immigrants settled in the "Central End", today's Little Italy, and the city was the 3rd most Italian in the state by 1910.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Their newspapers were the weekly *La Tribuna de Connecticut* (1906–1908) and later *La Sentinella* (1920–1948) The West End along Wordin Avenue, known as "Hunktown", grew into one of the largest Hungarian communities in the US.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] It was visited by Hungarian republicans trying to take down the Austro-Hungarian monarchy, in order to garner support.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The West Side nearby was home to Slovenians, French-Canadians and Swedish immigrants.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By 1910 Bridgeport had grown into second largest city in Connecticut at 102,052, behind New Haven.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Between 1910 and 1920, during World War I, the city's population exploded from 102,054 to 143,555, due to the city's role in the First World War.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport had the largest factory in the world at the time, the new Remington Arms plant on Boston Avenue (on the East Side).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Built in 1915, it had 13 separate buildings, each of them 5 stories, connected by a long corridor half a mile long.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The purpose of the building was to fulfil a company order from the Russian tzar for a million rifles and 100 million rounds of ammunition.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The construction site was protected by the National Guard to prevent Bolshevik arson.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The factory by 1916 employed 16,000 people and led to the construction of "Remington City" in the Mill Hill neighborhood, and "Remington Village" in the East End, by Remington Arms.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the summer of 1915, a series of strikes imposed the eight-hour day on the town's factories; rather than moving business elsewhere, the success spread the eight-hour day throughout the Northeast.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Due to housing shortages in many US cities during World War I, the federal government created the US Housing Corporation.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] This resulted in 7 USHC housing developments being built in Bridgeport, notably Seaside Village in the South End and Black Rock Gardens in Black Rock.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By this point, Remington Arms was producing 50% of America's cartridges during the war, with 17,000 employees, and homes for new workers were needed.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The factory became a General Electric plant after the war.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The First World War had continued the city's expansion so that, on the eve of the Great Depression, there were more than 500 factories in Bridgeport, including Columbia Records' primary pressing plant and a Singer Sewing Machine factory.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The 1920s saw the city's population stabilize at 143,555 after the war.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Roaring Twenties brought more leisure and entertainment.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1919, the city of Bridgeport bought Pleaseure Beach (also known as Steepchase Island) for $220,000.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Pleasure Beach was an amusement park and beach on an island in the East End next to Stratford.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1920, the city parks commissioner began the process of creating a zoo in Beardsley Park.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport a stop became for performances with around 20 theatres.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 1922 was the year the elegantly designed Majestic and Poli Palace theatres, were built downtown, along with the Savoy Hotel.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Poli Palace theatre (built by Sylvester Poli) was the largest theatre in the state of Connecticut, with gilded hand-carved moldings and vaulted ceilings.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1928, the city bought an 800-acre (320 ha) racetrack and landing field in Lordship to construct Bridgeport Airport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Spanish immigration in 1920 and 1921 brought hundreds of migrants from Spain, particularly from Pedreguer, Valencia, where "practically the entire town migrated" to Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] During the Great Depression the city elected Socialist party candidate Jasper McLevy as mayor in 1933.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] McLevy's election made headlines as a New England city had a socialist mayor.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Known for cutting costs, he would serve as mayor for 12 terms, finally losing in 1957.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Great Migration led southern African-Americans to Bridgeport around the 1930s (thanks to railroads) along with black foreigners (such as Cape Verdean), By 1930, Bridgeport had the third largest percentage of African Americans in New England.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Italian population by 1930 had more than doubled, now the city's largest ethnic group.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The build-up to World War II helped the city's recovery in the late 1930s.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Suburban development made its expansion into the undeveloped North End neighborhood.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] On Park Avenue in 1962 the Museum of Art, Science and Industry (MASI) was opened to the public, today's Discovery Museum and Planetarium.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Known for the newly developed approach of hands on-exhibits, the Museum became science oriented later on.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Continued development of new suburban housing outside of Bridgeport in the city's adjacent suburbs such as Fairfield and Milford attracted middle and upper-class residents, leaving the city with a higher proportion of poor.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By the 1960s, Puerto Ricans had begun to immigrate to settle to Bridgeport in large numbers, and by about 1970 had made up 10% of the city's population, or 15,000 people, the largest Puerto Rican population in Connecticut, and they would continue to grow.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Groups such as the local Young Lords branch organized themselves on East Main Street, leading to activism to advance the Puerto Rican community with increased access to health care, better housing, food and an end to poverty and police brutality.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As cities across the country were renovating their central business district after the war, Bridgeport attempted its own urban renewal projects in its old downtown in the early 1960s during the construction of the highways.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Hunktown, with a population of 15,000 and the Irish neighborhood in the South End were demolished and replaced with highways and an industrial park.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Trumbull Shopping Park was built just outside Bridgeport city limits in Trumbull in 1965, Connecticut's first fully enclosed shopping mall.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport under Mayor Tedesco went under the 52-acre (21 ha) State Street redevelopment project, demolishing 52 acres of State Street, clearing the land for development.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Replaced with modern high-rise office buildings, parking, the Route 8/25 expressway towards Waterbury and Newtown, and a shopping mall at its core.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Large parts of Main Street were demolished in what was called the Congress Street Renewal project, nothing was built on the land.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Constructed with federal funding, on Lafayette Boulevard and Broad Street, the 450,000 acre, 2 story (with basement) Lafayette Shopping Plaza was erected, a downtown shopping mall with a Sears and a Gimbels department store as anchors connected to it.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Military contracts during the 1950s and 1960s enabled the Bridgeport-Lycoming division of AVCO, founded 1951, to employ at times more than 12,000 people, building tanks, helicopters, and other military hardware.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Decreased demand led to layoffs, and then closure in 1984.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Other examples of urban development include two city landmarks, the 12-story 855 Main Street (People's Savings Bank building), and 18-floor Park City Plaza, (State National Bank building) built 1972.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The plan for three identical towers never materialized, due to the Oil Crisis and corporate vacancies.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As such, most skyscraper construction models for downtown Bridgeport from the 70s were never built, unlike Hartford (a city already home to major insurance companies) or Stamford.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Much of north downtown Bridgeport would end up abandoned, neglected and boarded up as department and discount stores closed, leaving only federal and municipal buildings along now empty lots.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Restructuring of heavy industry starting after the mid-20th century caused the loss of thousands of jobs and residents.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Like other urban centers in Connecticut, Bridgeport suffered during the deindustrialization of the United States in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Pleasure Beach was sold 5 years after a rollercoaster caught fire.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The old Bridgeport station caught fire in 1978.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In September 1978, Bridgeport teachers went on a 19-day strike due to deadlocked contract negotiations.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A court order, as well as a state law that made strikes by public workers illegal in Connecticut, resulted in 274 teachers being arrested and jailed.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In November 1978, a wave of arson passed through the city's East side, with the fire chief calling it as a microcosm of "the Bronx".
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The city suffered from overall mismanagement, for which several city officials were convicted, contributing to the economic and social decline.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The once busy Lafayette Shopping Plaza began to lose customers after Gimbel's closed in 1984.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Replaced with a Read's store, the mall was later bought by Hi-Ho Industries and renamed "Hi-Ho Mall", until it closed in 1993 and became Housatonic Community College in 1997.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] That's economic power, right?" In 1985, Bridgeport was still Connecticut's chief manufacturing center, its major industries including General Electric, Remington Shaver, Bryant Electric, and Raybestos plants.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A *New York Times* in 1985 stated Bridgeport was the fifth largest banking center in New England, with five of the banks based Bridgeport having assets of more than $6 billion.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The largest scissors, shear and surgical materials manufacturer in the world by 1946, Bridgeport-based ACME Shear closed its Bridgeport plant in 1996 due to mergers and acquisitions.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The industrial operations relocated to Fremont, North Carolina.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Between 1984 and 1989 the construction of the new $75 million headquarters for People's United Bank, the second largest bank in New England.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport in 1989 had more homicides per capita than any Northeastern US city over 100,000 people.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport had a smaller police force than smaller cities like Hartford or New Haven, yet hiring due to city financial issues, having not recovered from the exodus of manufacturing companies, would result in even higher taxes for residents.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1991, the city filed for bankruptcy protection but was declared solvent by a federal court.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Moran lost the election to Joseph Ganim, at 33 years old, the youngest person to hold that office. and under him the city was able to begin redevelopment with the construction of the Arena at Harbor Yard and the Ballpark at Harbor Yard.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport made numerous efforts at revitalization.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In a proposal in 1995, Las Vegas developer Steve Wynn was to build a large casino, but that project failed due to traffic concerns.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The project was opposed as rival Donald Trump feared a Bridgeport casino would harm his Atlantic City properties and proposed to build a theme park and potential casino on the same site.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] New waves of migrants from places such as Brazil, Jamaica, Vietnam, Laos, Cambodia, Mexico, and other nations arrived in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Immigrants from Brazil, after the nation's inflation crisis, established themselves in the city due to the large Portuguese population already present, easing the language barrier.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was a common second US destination for Vietnamese refugees "There's already an established community here, so that's why they come," from the New York Times in 1996.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Along with them, Thai, Koreans, Chinese, and especially Laotians and Cambodians established themselves in the city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Likewise, the population from other Central and South American nations continued to increase while the Cuban population continued to decrease.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] "There has been a big shift in ethnic groups.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Just look at the restaurants that have opened in the last few years—Mexican, Brazilian, Chilean and Jamaican." an interviewee, local chamber of council president Paul Timpanelli stated in 2000 according to the Connecticut Post.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 1999, city-owned Sikorsky Memorial Airport ceased its commercial regional flight offerings.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2003, Mayor Ganim was involved in a corruption scandal after being investigated by the FBI as he received gifts from developers in exchange for being allowed to build in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] He was sentenced to federal prison, and was replaced by John Fabrizi.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the early 21st century, Bridgeport has taken steps toward redevelopment of its downtown and other neighborhoods.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2004, artists' lofts were developed in the former Read's Department Store on Broad Street.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Several other rental conversions have been completed, including the 117-unit Citytrust bank building on Main Street.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Great Recession halted, at least temporarily, two major mixed-use projects including a $1-billion waterfront development at Steel Point, but other redevelopment projects have proceeded, such as the condominium conversion project in Bijou Square.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2009, the City Council under Mayor Finch approved a new master plan for development, designed both to promote redevelopment in selected areas and to protect existing residential neighborhoods.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2010, the Bridgeport Housing Authority and a local health center announced plans to build a $20 million medical and housing complex at Albion Street, making use of federal stimulus funds and designed to replace some of the housing lost with the demolition of Father Panik Village.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Steel Point (or Steelpointe) project of Bridgeport's on the lower portion of the East Side finally led to the construction of a big box retailer in 2013, along with other stores, shops, and a lighthouse with a marina and oyster bar).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The plan for high-end mixed use apartments is in place, although concerns about gentrification have been raised.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A new proposed train station in East Bridgeport, meant to be completed in 2021, was postponed in 2019.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] By 2013 the city and local business owners agreed that work needed to be done in the downtown area north of Fairfield Avenue, nicknamed Downtown North, above.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Made up of old empty brick buildings which were neglected for years, the city and developers began their rehabilitation starting in 2015, most of which are now converted apartments or retail.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport's downtown renovation has resulted in various restaurants, the renovation of the Bishop Arcade Mall, a comedy club, and theatres.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A 2022 plan to renovate McLevy Hall is in place.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In 2017, MGM had announced plans to build a waterfront casino and shopping center in the city, awaiting approval by the state government.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] If built, the development would have created 2,000 permanent jobs and about 5,779 temporary jobs.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] After a legal battle with the Mohegan and Pequot tribes on the right to build a casino in Connecticut, the project "appears to be dead", and tenants such as Bridgeport Boatworks now occupy the proposed space.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The construction of Honey Locust Square began on the East End, which when complete will house a supermarket (something the neighborhood lacks), a public library, a health center, and a retail building.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] On March 10, 1860, Abraham Lincoln spoke in the city's Washington Hall, an auditorium at the old Bridgeport City Hall (now McLevy Hall), at the corner of State and Broad Streets.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The largest room in the city was packed, and a crowd formed outside, as well.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Lincoln received a standing ovation before taking the 9:07 pm train that night back to Manhattan.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A plaque marks the site where Lincoln spoke; later that year, he was elected president.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Martin Luther King Jr. spoke three times at the Klein Auditorium during the 1960s, as well as at the University of Bridgeport and the original Central High School (today Bridgeport City Hall)., as well as in Bridgeport City Hall.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bush spoke before a small group of Connecticut business people and officials at the Playhouse on the Green in 2006.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] President Barack Obama also spoke at the Harbor Yard arena in 2010 to gain support for the campaign of Democratic Governor Dan Malloy.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport lies along Long Island Sound at the mouth of the Pequonnock River.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport has many distinct neighborhoods, divided into five geographic areas: Downtown, the East Side, the North End, the South End, and the West Side.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Under the Köppen climate classification, Bridgeport straddles the humid subtropical climate (*Cfa*) and humid continental climate (*Dfa*) zones with long, hot summers, and cool to cold winters, with precipitation spread fairly evenly throughout the year.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport, like the rest of coastal Connecticut, lies in the broad transition zone between the colder continental climates of the northern United States and southern Canada to the north, and the warmer temperate and subtropical climates of the middle and south Atlantic states to the south.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The warm/hot season in Bridgeport is from mid-April through early November.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Late day thundershowers are common in the hottest months (June, July, August, September), despite the mostly sunny skies.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The cool/cold season is from late November though mid-March.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Winter weather is far more variable than summer weather along the Connecticut coast, ranging from sunny days with higher temperatures to cold and blustery conditions with occasional snow.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Like much of the Connecticut coast and nearby Long Island, NY, most of the winter precipitation is rain or a mix and rain and wet snow in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport averages about 29 inches (75 cm) of snow annually, compared to inland areas like Hartford and Albany which average 45–60 inches (110–150 cm) of snow annually.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Although infrequent, tropical cyclones (hurricanes/tropical storms) have struck Connecticut and the Bridgeport metropolitan area.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Hurricane landfalls have occurred along the Connecticut coast in 1903, 1938, 1944, 1954 (Carol), 1960 (Donna), Hurricane Gloria in 1985, and Hurricane Sandy in 2012.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport lies in USDA garden hardiness zone 7a, averaging about 92 days annually with freeze.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The coastal location of Bridgeport allows it to be milder than locations well south but inland.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] For example, the record coldest low temperature at Atlanta is −8 °F, while the record coldest at Bridgeport is −7 °F.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Coastal Connecticut is the broad transition zone where so-called "subtropical indicator" plants such as cold hardy palms and other broadleaf evergreens can successfully be cultivated.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As such, southern magnolias, needle palms, windmill palm, loblolly pines, and crape myrtles are grown in private and public gardens.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Like much of coastal Connecticut, Long Island, New York, and coastal New Jersey, the growing season is rather long in Bridgeport—averaging 210 days from April 8 to November 5 according to the National Weather Service in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The average monthly temperature ranges from 31.4 °F (−0.3 °C) in January to 75.7 °F (24.3 °C) in July.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Precipitation averages 44.9 inches (1,140 mm) annually, and is somewhat evenly distributed throughout the year, with March and April the wettest months.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As is typical of coastal Connecticut, snow cover does not usually last long, with an average of 33 days per winter with snow cover of at least 1 inch (2.5 cm).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As of the 2010 census, there were 144,229 people living in the city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The racial makeup of the city residents was 39.6% White; 34.6% Black or African American; 3.4% Asian; and 4.3% from two or more races.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A total of 38.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] There were 50,307 households, out of which 34.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 35.0% were married couples living together, 24.0% had a female householder with no husband present, and 34.9% were non-families.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 29.0% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.3% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The average household size was 2.70 and the average family size was 3.34.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In the city, the population was spread out, with 28.4% under the age of 18, 11.2% from 18 to 24, 30.5% from 25 to 44, 18.4% from 45 to 64, and 11.5% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] For every 100 females, there were 91.2 males.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.3 males.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The median income for a household in the city was $34,658, and the median income for a family was $39,571.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Males had a median income of $32,430 versus $26,966 for females.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The per capita income for the city was $16,306.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] About 16.2% of families and 18.4% of the population were below the poverty line, including 24.8% of those under age 18 and 13.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] According to the 2020 five-year community survey, 48.2% of Bridgeport's population speaks a different primary language at home other than English, 33.8% percent of the city's total population speaks Spanish at home, and 22.5% speak English less than very well.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport has the largest percentage and population of Hispanic Americans in the state of Connecticut.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 45,270 people (31%) of Bridgeport's population is foreign born in 2010.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Other than Puerto Ricans, 5.4% of Bridgeport's population was noted under Mexican in 2013, a number that has grown to 5.8% (8,479 people) in the 2020 five-year American Community Survey, meaning Bridgeport has the largest Mexican population in New England.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Dominicans are 5,248 (3.53%) of Bridgeport's population.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The total Latino Central American population (Guatemalans, Salvadorians, Nicaraguans, Hondurans, Costa Ricans, Panamanians) is 6,701 people total in the city (4.507%).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 8,454 South Americans (5.697%); 4,020 Equadorians, 2,326 Colombians, Peruvians, and then populations from every Latin American nation except Bolivia can be found, with the smallest group being Paraguayans at 16 people according to the census.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport also has the largest Cuban population in the state, with more than 1,000 of the state's 10,600 Cubans living in Bridgeport, although down from the at least 5,000 Cubans in Bridgeport in 1980, and even more before that time in the 1950s according to the CTPost.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport was once a major destination for migrating Cubans, but many families have since moved to the city's suburbs or Florida.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport, along with Danbury, CT were considered as a potential locations for a new Ecuadorian consulate, but it instead opened in New Haven, CT, due to its immigrant welcoming mayor, in 2008.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As for Portuguese-speaking peoples, the city also has the 12th largest Cape Verdean population in the country.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The group settled in the Hollow to work in factories and established a social club in the 1940s.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Cape Verdean Association of Bridgeport is located in the Hollow today.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Portuguese community in the city is the largest in the state and the population primarily hails from the Tras Os Montes region of Portugal according to a 2018 research study, and the Hollow is considered the "Portuguese section" of Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The large Brazilian population in Bridgeport and Danbury led to the opening of a Brazilian consulate in the state capital of Hartford.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Migration to Connecticut began in the 90s, social networks brought immigrants from Governador Valadares, Minas Gerais in Brazil to Bridgeport, CT and Framingham, MA.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Fairfield County has the 7th largest Brazilian population of the United States, and 1/3rd of them live within Bridgeport's city limits, most of whom reside in the city's North End and St.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] A small population of people from various majority-Muslim nations exists along with Kurds, at least 4,000 according to an estimate by a local mosque in 2008.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport Public Schools now observes Eid al-Fitr, effective 2024, thanks to a campaign by city 8th graders from Park City Magnet School, which found 10% of the school body was Muslim in a school project.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bengali in 2022 was the fifth most common primary language for Bridgeport Public School students (behind English, Spanish, Portuguese, and Haitian Creole, and is followed by Arabic at sixth place).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] There is also a sizeable Kurdish population in Bridgeport, primarily from Iraq.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] In total (and counting East and Southeast Asians), Bridgeport had 7,725 Asian residents according to the 2021 5 year American Community Survey, up from 2020's count, 5,553 Asians.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The largest national origin groups and their estimated populations are Vietnamese (1,258 people), Indian (1,153 people), Chinese, excluding Taiwanese and Pakistanis (both 982 people), and Filipinos (729 people).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Other groups with over 500 people include Laotians and Cambodians, Bangladeshi Americans in the city numbered 385 people in the survey.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Jamaicans, the state's largest foreign-born group, have a significant presence in Bridgeport, with 6.3% of Bridgeport's population being Jamaican in 2013.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Bridgeport in 2013 was 10.2% non-Hispanic West Indian.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] At least 92 languages are spoken as primary languages by Bridgeport Public School students according to district data in 2022.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] 3,145 students are missing data in primary language.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The Bridgeport-Stamford metropolitan area (i.e.: Fairfield County) is home to the 7th largest percentage of Italian ancestry in the country (the population is 16.5% Italian).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Italian Americans until 1985 were the largest ethnic group in Bridgeport itself, and had been since the 1920s.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] According to 2010 census data, the Bridgeport MSA, containing all of Fairfield County, is the most economically unequal region in America, with 57% of the wealth going to the top income quintile.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] As of the census of 2000, there were 139,529 people, 50,307 households, and 32,749 families living in the city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The population density was 8,720.9 inhabitants per square mile (3,367.2/km2).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] There were 54,367 housing units at an average density of 3,398.1 per square mile (1,312.0/km2).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] The racial makeup of the city was 45.0% White, 30.8% African American, 0.5% Native American, 3.3% Asian, 0.1% Pacific Islander.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p01] Hispanic or Latino people of any race were 31.9% of the population.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Since the decline of its industrial sector beginning in the middle of the 20th century, Bridgeport has gradually adjusted to a service-based economy.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] As late as 1985, the city was still home to company plants such as General Electric, with 1,900 employees, and Remington Products, with 900, both of which are now closed.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bryant Electric didn't close its plant until 1988.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The last major factory to close was the Sikorsky helicopter plant in 2015.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Various famous industrial companies, that were founded and based in Bridgeport, such as ACME Sheer, Fortune 1000 Hubbell Incorporated, etc. are now based in suburban Shelton, two towns away.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Subway, which started out in Bridgeport in 1965, is now based in Milford.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Though a level of industrial activity continues, healthcare, finance, and education have become the centerpieces of Bridgeport's economy.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The two largest employers in the city are Bridgeport's primary hospitals, Bridgeport Hospital and St.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Park City Hospital in the South End closed in 1993 and was reopened in 2010 as elderly and homeless housing units.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In April 2022, M&T Bank of Buffalo, New York, merged with Bridgeport-based People's United Financial.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The combined company is now the 11th largest bank in the United States, and gave M&T a foothold in the New England market, in total serving 12 states.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Although M&T laid off Bridgeport employees (which made national headlines), the company as part of this effort made Bridgeport Center the regional M&T headquarters of New England.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport was the annual home to Gathering of the Vibes, a weekend-long arts, music and camping festival, until it ended in 2015.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Beginning in 2022, Bridgeport played host to the Sound on Sound Music Festival, at Seaside Park.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Past performers included; John Mayer, Red Hot Chili Peppers, Dave Matthews Band, Hozier, and The Roots.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The festival was rebranded in 2024 to Soundside Music Festival.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The 2025 Soundside Music Festival was cancelled.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport Symphony, established in 1945, performs at Bridgeport's 1,400-seat Klein Memorial Auditorium.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Gustav Meier directed the orchestra from 1972 to 2013.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport metropolitan area is home to the Maritime Aquarium in Norwalk, 30 minutes from downtown Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] One of the two aquariums in Connecticut, the aquarium focuses on Long Island Sound as well as creatures and conservation efforts from around the world.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport was once home to a Little Asia along Wood Avenue in the West Side, established in 2012 by local business owners with a sign and a festival every year.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] By 2016 the name had fallen out of use, and the committee no longer exists.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The more or less 3 or 4 block area is still home to Asian restaurants, an insurance and tax agency with Vietnamese, Mandarin, Laotian, Cantonese as well as Spanish language services, and a Vietnamese grocery store.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] NerdWallet ranked Bridgeport the 100th most foodie city in the United States, 2nd in Connecticut behind New Haven (which was ranked #97).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Nerdwallet in 2022 ranked Bridgeport as the 17th most ethnically diverse city in the United States, making it the most diverse in New England, and the third most diverse in the New York Metropolitan Area in an annual ranking.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is #28 on Niche.com "2022 Most Diverse Cities in America" list.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport's Madison Avenue, and Hollow Brazilian restaurants, located alongside various Portuguese ones, have been mentioned by publications such as the *New York Times*.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Examples include churascaria restaurants.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is "among the top cities in the state to immerse yourself in Brazilian traditions" according to CTBites.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Azteca was ranked among the best Mexican restaurants in Connecticut in 2020 according to *Connecticut Magazine*, along with Pho Hong Thom and Pho Saigon in Bridgeport's Little Asia on the West Side for best Vietnamese places in the state.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Total Mortgage Arena serves as the city's sports and hospitality center.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Seating 10,000, the Arena serves as the home rink of the Bridgeport Islanders American Hockey League team, the farm team of the New York Islanders of the National Hockey League.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Starting in 2024, it also serves as the home of the New York Sirens of the Professional Women's Hockey League.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The arena served as the temporary home of the Westchester Knicks of the NBA G League (the farm team for the NBA New York Knicks) from 2021 to 2023 when the team's home stadium, Westchester County Center in White Plains, New York iwas being used as a vaccination clinic.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] For college teams, Total Mortgage serves as the home court of Fairfield University's basketball team.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Ballpark at Harbor Yard served as a minor-league baseball stadium from 1998 to 2017.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It was built in 1998 to serve as the homefield of the Bridgeport Bluefish.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] From 2001 to 2003 it was the homefield for the Bridgeport Barrage, a Major League Lacrosse team.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is downtown on a former brownfield site.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is visually prominent to commuters on I-95 or on passing trains.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] On August 8, 2017, Mayor Joe Ganim announced that the Bluefish would be ending their 20-year stint at the ballpark at the end of the 2017 season.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The ballpark was converted into an amphitheatre.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bluefish played their final home game at the park on September 17, 2017, losing by a score of 9–2 to the Somerset Patriots.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Kennedy Stadium serves as a community sports facility.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, it was the home of an Atlantic Coast Football League minor league football team, the Bridgeport Jets, a New York Jets farm team also known locally as the Hi-Ho Jets due to their sponsorship by the (Hi-Ho) D'Addario construction company.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Fairfield University is in the neighboring town of Fairfield, and many of the athletic teams play on campus.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Only the men's and women's basketball teams play in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Nutmeg Curling Club, one of two curling clubs in Connecticut, is in Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is the home club of the 2013 USA Mixed National Champions, led by club members Derek Surka and Charissa Lin.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The club is a member of the Grand National Curling Club Region.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport native Jim O'Rourke was the first baseball player to earn a hit in National League history in 1876.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The founder and original owner of the Brooklyn Dodgers, Charles Ebbets, married his second wife in Bridgeport in 1922, five years before his death.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In early 2024, MLS Next Pro awarded an expansion team to Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Connecticut United FC plan to play at a new stadium to be located on the waterfront at a former dog-racing track, as stadium plans were approved by the Bridgeport government in November 2023.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Amateur soccer team GZS Bridgeport play in the UPSL, playing home games at Kennedy Stadium.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city has 1,300 acres of public space, with a pocket park in nearly every neighborhood.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport's public park system led to its official nickname, "the Park City".
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city's first public park was the westerly portion of McLevy Green, first set aside as a public square in 1806; the Clinton Park Militia Grounds (1666) and Old Mill Green (1717) were set aside earlier as public commons by the towns of Fairfield and Stratford, respectively.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Washington Park in 1850 was located in the center of East Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] As the city rapidly grew in population, residents recognized the need for more public parks and by 1864, Barnum, Nathaniel Wheeler and Colonel William Noble donated approximately 44 acres (18 ha) to create Seaside Park, now increased by acquisition and landfill to 375 acres (152 ha).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In 1878, over 100 acres (40 ha) of land bordering the Pequonnock River was added as Beardsley Park.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Frederick Law Olmsted, who designed New York City's Central Park, designed both Seaside and Beardsley Parks.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Over time, more parks were added including 35-acre (14 ha) Beechwood Park and Pleasure Beach, home to an amusement park for many years.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Went Field on the West End, between Wordin Avenue and Norman Street, used to be the winter headquarters of Barnum's circus.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city is governed by the mayor-council system.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Twenty members of the city council are elected from districts.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The mayor is elected at-large by the entire city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is notable for having had a socialist mayor for 24 years, Jasper McLevy, who served from 1933 to 1957.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Ganim, is a convicted felon who was sentenced to nine years in prison after conviction in 2003 of 16 federal counts including racketeering, extortion, conspiracy, bribery, mail fraud, and filing false tax returns arising from Ganim's "role in a six-year scheme to shake down city contractors…".
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Fabrizi admitted that he had used cocaine while in office.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is recognized for its polarizing political culture.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Mayor Ganim has served the city seven terms since first taking office in 1991.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] After his release from prison in 2015, Ganim announced his mayoral campaign to serve a sixth term in office.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] His campaign ran on a theme of providing him with a "second-chance," as he was renowned for his work of escaping the city from bankruptcy and build its economy from a post-industrial standpoint.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport's Democratic Town Committee has the authority to nominate and endorse Democratic candidates running for local office, and they have the resources to outperform challenger slates that may compete with them.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The chairman is former state representative and local restaurateur, Mario Testa.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport votes Democratic at the presidential level.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In 1972 Richard Nixon was the last Republican to win the city; since then Democrats have prevailed, often by comfortable margins, the lone exception being 1984 when Walter Mondale carried the city by just 76 votes (0.16 percent) over Ronald Reagan.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport has one of the highest property tax rates in Connecticut.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] In 2016, Bridgeport enacted a 29% increase in the property tax rate, among the highest one-year property tax rate increases in recent U.S. history, in an effort to reduce the municipal deficit.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] A citywide reassessment in 2015 determined that the value of taxable property in the city was $6 billion, a decline of $1 billion; the property tax increases, combined with property value decreases, have been a consistent political issue in the city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is home to the University of Bridgeport, Housatonic Community College, Saint Vincent's College, and the Yeshiva Gedola of Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Yeshiva Gedola is the home of the Bridgeport Community Kollel, a rabbinic fellowship program.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The University of Bridgeport's Ernest C.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Trefz School of Business offers undergraduate and graduate programs.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Sacred Heart University is located in the neighboring suburb of Fairfield on the town line, with its campus extending into the North End of Bridgeport on Park Avenue.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Many of its students live in the city's North End.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is the second largest Catholic University in New England (behind Boston College).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Sacred Heart has campuses in nearby Stamford, as well as Griswold, CT and Dingle, Ireland, as well as St.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The University of Bridgeport has secondary campuses in Waterbury and Stamford.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport Area (made up of the surrounding towns) is home to Fairfield University in neighboring Fairfield, and Western Connecticut State University in Danbury.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city's public school system has 30 elementary schools, three comprehensive high schools, two alternative programs and an interdistrict vocational aquaculture school.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The system has about 20,800 students, making the Bridgeport Public Schools the second largest school system in Connecticut after Hartford.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is ranked #158 out of the 164 Connecticut school districts.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The school system employs a professional staff of more than 1,700.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city has started a large school renovation and construction program, with plans for new schools and modernization of existing buildings.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport is also home to private schools including Bridgeport Hope School (K–8), Bridgeport International Academy (grades 9–12), Catholic Academies of Bridgeport (Pre-K–8), Kolbe Cathedral High School (9–12), St.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Bridgeport was NBC's pioneer UHF TV test site from December 29, 1949, to August 23, 1952; the equipment from the "Operation Bridgeport" tests was later deployed commercially at KPTV in Portland, Oregon (1952–1957).
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Sikorsky Memorial Airport in neighboring Stratford is owned by the City of Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It once provided regional flights to major cities, but commercial operations at the airport were terminated in November 1999.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Interstate 95 and the Route 8/Route 25 Connector meet in Downtown Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] I-95 runs east–west near the coast heading towards New York City to the southwest and Providence to the northeast.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Routes 8 and 25 run north–south across the city, with the two routes splitting just north of the city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Route 8 continues towards Waterbury and Torrington and Route 25 continues towards the Danbury area.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Both Routes 8 and 25 connect to the Merritt Parkway in the adjacent town of Trumbull.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] 1 (the Boston Post Road), which runs east–west north of Downtown, and Main Street, which runs north–south towards Trumbull center.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city also has several secondary state highways, namely, Route 127 (East Main Street), Route 130 (Connecticut Avenue, Stratford Avenue, Fairfield Avenue and Water Street), and the Huntington Turnpike.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport Traction Company provided streetcar service in the region until 1937.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Housatonic Railroad carried passengers North through the Pequonnock and Housatonic Valleys before 1933.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The city is connected to nearby New York City by both Amtrak and Metro-North commuter trains, which serve Bridgeport's Metro-North station.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Many residents commute to New York jobs on these trains, and the city to some extent is developing as an outpost of New York–based workers seeking cheaper rents and larger living spaces.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Connecting service is also available to Waterbury via Metro-North, and New Haven via Amtrak and Metro-North.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Shoreline East service links Old Saybrook and New London with New Haven, which extends to Bridgeport and Stamford during weekday rush hours only.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport & Port Jefferson Ferry service runs from Bridgeport across Long Island Sound to Port Jefferson, New York; the four vessels *Grand Republic*, *P.T.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Barnum*, Long Island and *Park City* transport both automobiles and passengers.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Greater Bridgeport Transit Authority (GBTA) provides bus service to Bridgeport and its immediate suburbs.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Route 2 the Coastal Link goes west to Norwalk and east to the Connecticut Post Mall in Milford, from where Connecticut Transit can bring passengers to the New Haven Green.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Greyhound and Peter Pan Bus Lines both offer intercity bus service to points throughout the Northeast and points beyond.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport Fire Department provides fire protection and emergency medical services at the Basic life support level to the city of Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Bridgeport Police Department is the primary law enforcement agency in Bridgeport, Fairfield County, Connecticut, United States.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] It is responsible for most law enforcement within the geographical boundaries of City of Bridgeport.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] The Connecticut State Police Troop G barracks is located in Bridgeport but they do not primarily perform law enforcement functions in the city.
[src:bridgeport-connecticut/bridgeport-connecticut-p02] Emergency medical services are provided by American Medical Response at the paramedic level.
